  "issue_number": 15269,
  "issue_title": "rubocop.yml Include directives consider parent directories",
  "issue_body": "### Before submitting\n\n- [x] I have searched the existing issues and this hasn't been reported yet.\n- [x] I am running the latest stable version of RuboCop.\n\n### Issue type\n\nOther\n\n### Cop name\n\n_No response_\n\n### Steps to reproduce the problem\n\n1. Create a rubocop configuration using an include pattern such as `**/app/**/*.rb` (for example https://github.com/rubocop/rubocop-rails/blob/c6d6c6886af15ae3c4439ed41f45f3036b9cba6c/config/default.yml#L795)\n2. Place your application in a file path that happens to include `app` as a component (e.g. `/usr/src/app`)\n3. Have violations in a path in the project other than `app` (e.g. `spec/myfile.rb`)\n4. Run rubocop, and see that rubocop has flagged violations in `myfile.rb` that is not covered by the include pattern\n5. Move the app to a file path that does not have `app` in the ancestors, and see that rubocop does _not_ flag violations in `myfile.rb`\n\nSee https://github.com/maths22/rubocop-include-bug-demo for a full (super tiny) demonstration of the issue\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nRubocop should behave consistently regardless of the parent directory the project lives in\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nRubocop include patterns wind up applying to the parent directories of a project. Note that _exclude_ directories do not, as rubocop has explicit logic that converts those into absolute paths during config processing.\n\n### RuboCop configuration\n\n```yaml\nAllCops:\n  NewCops: enable\n\nStyle/StringLiterals:\n  Include:\n    - '**/app/**/*.rb'\n```\n\n### RuboCop version\n\n```shell\n$ rubocop -V\n1.74.0 (using Parser 3.3.7.2, rubocop-ast 1.41.0, analyzing as Ruby 3.1, running on ruby 3.1.6) [arm64-darwin23]\n```",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-15T16:28:28Z",
